3 PCA with standardized variables

human_std <- scale(human)
pca_human_std <- prcomp(human_std)

s2 <- summary(pca_human_std)
s2
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2     PC3     PC4     PC5     PC6
## Standard deviation     2.0708 1.1397 0.87505 0.77886 0.66196 0.53631
## Proportion of Variance 0.5361 0.1624 0.09571 0.07583 0.05477 0.03595
## Cumulative Proportion  0.5361 0.6984 0.79413 0.86996 0.92473 0.96069
##                            PC7     PC8
## Standard deviation     0.45900 0.32224
## Proportion of Variance 0.02634 0.01298
## Cumulative Proportion  0.98702 1.00000
pca_pr <- round(100*s2$importance[2, ], digits = 1)

pca_pr
##  PC1  PC2  PC3  PC4  PC5  PC6  PC7  PC8 
## 53.6 16.2  9.6  7.6  5.5  3.6  2.6  1.3
pc_lab <- paste0(names(pca_pr), " (", pca_pr, "%)")

biplot(pca_human_std, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab[1], ylab = pc_lab[2])

4 Intepretation of the standardized PCA

In the standardized model the first components explain 53,6 % of the variance and the second dimension (PC2) explaints 16,2 % of the variance. PC3 has 9,5 % of the variance and 4 has 7,5 %. So the First dimension explains over half of the variance.
